         Cycle causes uncertainty, dampening investment as agents are risk averse

o    Exacerbated by heterogenous populations: low skilled workers more affected by recessions

         Growth is usually more important than stable growth for policy makers, but stabilising the business cycle may make growth easier

Extensions

Excessive sensitivity and smoothness suggest:

o    Habits

o    Irrational expectations

o    Demographic variance

o    Aggregation problem

o    Credit constraints:

MPC out of current income = 1 when credit constrained

o    Precautionary saving:

Hence with quadratic utility, variance of future income has no effect on the saving decision (known as certainty equivalence)

Note: not same as risk neutrality - utility is still concave (IARA)

 

If MU is concave (e.g. log utility), then ↑ variance of future income → ↑ savings ⇒ precautionary saving

 

Useful for helping to explain:

1.      Excess sensitivity

         If MU becomes more linear at a higher level of income/consumption, then precautionary savings decline with income, and consumption appears to increase with predictable changes in income

         Uncertainty means future expected income is worth less (in utility) than (certain) current income: future effectively faces higher discount rate. So present income matters more than future income

2.      Excess smoothness

         Some of the news regarding permanent income changes are diverted into precautionary saving

2.2 RICARDIAN VIEW

Automatic stabilisers

Budget deficit from ↓ T has no impact on AD

Budget deficit from ↑ G shifts AD with multiplier < 1

2.2.2 Multi-period Generalisation

See the 'Fiscal Policy' section for a more thorough analysis

So how current and future government expenditures are financed (i.e. raising taxes or accumulating debt) is irrelevant: only present value of government spending matters

 

Results that increasing government spending has negative wealth effects on consumption still hold (i.e. general equilibrium effects)

 

General results:

a.       Temporary changes in tax have no impact on aggregate demand

b.      Permanent changes in govt. spending have no impact on aggregate demand

c.       Temporary changes in govt. spending financed by borrowing have a short-term impact on AD (in the same direction) but at the cost of a permanent (smaller) change in the opposite direction in the long-term

e.g. if there is a temporary boost in govt. spending:

  Consumption in all future periods declines equally to smooth this by permanent income result

  Then in periods of temporary boost, total AD is increased

  But in periods after boost, total AD is decreased (since consumption has permanently declined)

d.      Temporary changes in govt. spending financed by taxes have the same impact as (c), derivable using results (a) and (c)

 

2.2.3 Relaxing assumptions

1.      Lump-sum, non-distortionary taxes not possible

Distortionary taxes reduce overall output by creating inefficiencies in economy (recall Micro tax theory)

So if taxes are distortionary then cutting taxes could ⇒ ↑

 

Hence, using (simplified) consumer budget constraint:

 

A cut in tax in may not be totally offset by a raise in since there is positive effect on output, so consumption increases (positive wealth effect)

 

2.      Consumers and government have different planning horizons

e.g. if governments plan for three periods, but consumers only plan for two:

 

So if a tax cut in is financed by a tax raise in , this generates a positive wealth effect for the current generation (who do not care about taxes in

Assumes imperfect (or non-existent) consumer altruism towards future generations

 

3.      Government faces lower interest rates than consumers

If government faces , and consumer faces

 

Then multi-period equation above becomes:

 

i.e. taxes do not cancel out, so timing of taxes matters (since cost for government to pay back debt differs from consumer)

 

Two-period version:

 

4.      Imperfect credit markets

a.       Private borrowing is at a higher interest rate than private saving / government financing

 

A debt-financed tax cut may benefit borrowers (B → C), leading to an overall expansion in average consumption

 

Effectively, it is as if government is borrowing on behalf of borrowers (cheaper, potentially a Pareto improvement) - although there is no guarantee this will affect AD

 

b.      Variable interest rates

Higher future taxation may make repayments more difficult so credit constraints tighten

Note how this is non-Ricardian but also non-Keynesian: tax cuts may dampen AD by making borrowing more difficult

Some models negate this effect by having the government 'lend' to borrowers (subsidies, welfare) as a replacement for the (more expensive) private lending

 

5.      Uncertainty in future tax changes

With quadratic utility, certainty equivalence implies that uncertainty over when taxes will change has no impact on utility

But excess sensitivity/smoothness seems to imply quadratic utility is unrealistic

 

Uncertainty with lump-sum taxes:

Uncertainty about taxes uncertainty about disposable income, inducing higher precautionary saving

Note how this is non-Ricardian but also non-Keynesian: running a short-term deficit may dampen consumption as people save more (due to uncertainty over when taxes will be raised again)

 

Uncertainty with proportional income taxes:

Higher tax rates reduce uncertainty so reduce precautionary saving

More standard Keynesian effect: short-term budget deficit boosts short-term consumption

 

 

3. The RBC Model

 

Typical setup:

         Classical economics

         Consumers maximise utility, firms maximise profits

         Flexible prices

         Complete markets, no externalities

         Business cycle driven by supply shocks, themselves caused by randomness in exogenous technological progress

Motivation for this result:

         Recall wage increases entail income and substitution effect

         Historical data suggest positive trend in real wages but no change in hours worked (i.e. labour supply)

         This implies that, for permanent changes, income and substitution effects cancel out

         Hence for temporary wage increases the income effect is diminished so substitution effect dominates ⇒ labour supply increases

Basic RBC Model

 

Evaluation

Importance of capital accumulation

If there was no investment, higher productivity in one period could not induce higher productivity in the next: labour supply is constant since income & substitution effects cancel

Savings induces labour supply when there is a positive technological shock, since saving allows for higher consumption in future periods (via capital accumulation in Solow-Swan model)

 

However, capital accumulation is a weak transmission mechanism (capital stock is slow to change even with volatile saving investment), hence high autocorrelation in shocks is required to match observations in data (labour supply as volatile as output)

 

Plausibility of elastic labour supply

In order to reflect strong cyclicality of labour supply observed in data, labour supply must be very elastic

 

Typically economic theory argues that individual labour supply is rather inelastic, but this can still be reconciled by considering:

                     i.Indivisibility of labour

Usually, workers are not presented with continuous choice of hours but a very discrete and restricted set of options (e.g. full-time, part-time, unemployed). Hence hours worked can 'jump around' by large amoutns even if invidiual labour supply is inelastic

                  ii.Implicit contract theory

Common for employers and employees to agree that future hours worked is positively dependent on performance of company correlation between hours worked and economic cycles

These can result in an elastic aggregate labour supply even if individual labour supply is inelastic

 

Plausibility of technological shocks driving business cycles

Difficulties in interpreting what technological shocks are (especially negative ones)

Emphasis on supply-side is controversial: see New Keynesian interpretation of short-term volatility

 

Empirics are mixed:

Kydland & Prescott estimate technology shocks account for 70% of business cycle volatility

Canova & de Nicolo estimate supply shocks to be less than 30%

 

Example in the debate around the 1930s Great Depression: some attribute the recession to the 'technology shock' of market intermediation, others argue it was a policy response distorting the market
